solutions.content:
One solution to this problem is to count the number of errors and "merge" as many errors as we can.

Repeat errors are defined as how many letters need to be changed to fit the repeat rule.
Lowercase, uppercase and digit errors are defined by how many of the 3 are missing.
Size errors are defined as 0 or the distance from n to an acceptable size. So n = 4 -> 2 and n = 22 -> -2.

We need to notice that the following can be merged
1. repeating letters, and missing lowercase, uppercase and digits
2. missing letters (n < 6) can be merged with above
3. extra letters can be merged with repeating letters

Lets first consider the case n < 6 or 6 <= n <= 20. If we have any errors we only need to find the maximum of them.

"aaaaaa" -> "aa1aaA" 
Repeat = 2, Missing = 2, Size = 0, Error = 2
In this example we see that we can merge errors from missing cases into repeating errors because it only requires a replacement.

"aa" -> "aaA1bc"
Repeat = 0, Missing = 2, Size = 4, Error = 4
In this example we can see that missing cases can be merged into size errors because the right insertion can fix both errors at the same time.

The harder case is when n > 20. Merging here is harder to keep track of and the rules from above may not apply because we can't simply insert. Missing cases can still be merged with repeat errors but they can not be merged with size errors because we are deleting instead of inserting.

"aaa" -> 1 deletion
"aaaa" -> 2 deletions
"aaaaa" -> 3 deletions

Here we have to consider the maximum amount of repeat errors we can merge into size errors. When we count the number of repeat errors we can keep a sorted list of the repeats we can fix with < 3 deletions. After those are gone the amount of deletions per repeat goes to 3. Since repeat errors and missing case errors still work the same we can merge them but only after we delete the number of repeat errors we can fix by deleting.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int strongPasswordChecker(string s) {
        bool lower = false;
        bool upper = false;
        bool digit = false;

        int repeating = 0;

        int n = s.size();

        vector<int> toRemove(3, 0);

        for(int i = 0; i < n;) {
            //Check if character is lowercase, uppercase, or digit and set those to true
            char c = s[i];
            if(48 <= c && c <= 57) {
                digit = true;
            } else if(65 <= c && c <= 90) {
                upper = true;
            } else if(97 <= c && c <= 122) {
                lower = true;
            }


            //count how many repeating numbers we have
            int counter = 1;
            while(i + counter < n && s[i + counter] == s[i]) {
                counter++;
            }

            //number of repeat errors goes up by 1 for every 3 repeating
            int errors = counter / 3;
            repeating += errors;

            //if we have a repeat error than push to a heap the number of deletions we need to 
            //remove a repeat error
            if(errors) {
                //maps 0 -> 1, 1 -> 2, 2 -> 3
                toRemove[(counter % 3)]++;
                toRemove[2] += errors - 1;
            }

            i += counter;
        }

        //count missing cases
        int toAdd = !lower + !upper + !digit;

        //get size error. 0 if there are no errors
        int toSize = 0;
        if(n > 20) {
            toSize = 20 - n;
        } else if(n < 6) {
            toSize = 6 - n;
        }

        if(toSize < 0) {
            //case n > 20

            int tmpSize = -toSize;
            //remove duplicates of (i + 1) size
            for(int i = 0; i <= 2; ++i) {
                int removed = min(tmpSize / (i + 1), toRemove[i]);
                tmpSize -= removed * (i + 1);
                repeating -= removed;
            }

            //if we have any case errors we can merge them with
            //repeat errors
            return max(toAdd, repeating) - toSize;

        } else {
            //case n <= 20
            //the error is simply the max becauses we can merge
            //every error with pretty much no consequence
            return max(toSize, max(toAdd, repeating));
        }
    }
};
```

