solutions.content:
The only tricky case is when the password is longer than 20 characters. In that case, use the deletions to cut down on the number of replacements you'll have to do. In order to accomplish that, first remove one from any subsequence of repeated characters of length 3, 6, 9, 12,.... That way, by removing just one from that subsequence, you've cut down on the number of replacements needed to break up the subsequence by 1. Then remove two from any subsequence of length 4, 7, 10, 13, .... Finally remove them three at a time from the rest of the subsequences. Of course, once it's short enough, you can stop removing characters.
```
class Solution {

    public int strongPasswordChecker(String password) {

        //First, look for subsequences of length 3 or more
        int[] tooLongFrequency = new int[50];
        int troublesomeLength = 3;
        int i = 0;
        while (i < password.length())
        {

            int currentIndex = i + 1;
            while ((currentIndex < password.length()) && (password.charAt(currentIndex) == password.charAt(i)))
            {
                currentIndex++;
            }//while
            int subsequenceLength = currentIndex - i;
            if (subsequenceLength >= 3)
            {
                tooLongFrequency[subsequenceLength]++;
            }//if

            i = currentIndex;

        }//while

        boolean hasLowerCase = false;
        boolean hasUpperCase = false;
        boolean hasDigit = false;
        for (i = 0; i < password.length(); i++)
        {
            if ((password.charAt(i) >= 'a') && (password.charAt(i) <= 'z'))
            {
                hasLowerCase = true;
            }//if
            else if ((password.charAt(i) >= 'A') && (password.charAt(i) <= 'Z'))
            {
                hasUpperCase = true;
            }//else if
            else if ((password.charAt(i) >= '0') && (password.charAt(i) <= '9'))
            {
                hasDigit = true;
            }//else if
        }//for

        int numDifferentTypesNeeded = (hasLowerCase ? 0 : 1) + (hasUpperCase ? 0 : 1) + (hasDigit ? 0 : 1);

        int minLength = 6;
        int maxLength = 20;

        int numEdits = 0;
        if (password.length() < minLength)
        {
            //TODO: this is not true for the general case. If minLength were larger than 6, we might have to do some replacements.
